WEBVTT

00:02.850 --> 00:08.796
you're listening to a teaching from Reality LA.

00:08.816 --> 00:14.983
I'll be preaching today on Acts chapter 15, the beginning of 16, and calling this everyday mission.

00:15.744 --> 00:25.754
And you know, throughout 2026, our vision as a church is to be on mission with Jesus and acts as a blueprint for mission in Los Angeles.

00:26.375 --> 00:29.138
And we've been in Acts for over a year,

00:29.282 --> 00:36.652
But since we've taken a little break, I want to refresh our collective memory of what this book is about and bring any new people up to speed.

00:37.393 --> 00:42.801
So in the New Testament, the four gospels tell the story of Jesus.

00:42.861 --> 00:52.254
They proclaim the good news that he lived the perfect life and died on the cross for our sins and rose from the grave to establish the kingdom of God on earth as it is in heaven.

00:52.975 --> 00:54.898
And then Acts is the sequel.

00:55.298 --> 01:06.969
It's the sequel that tells the story of the early church and how it went from a small group of disciples hiding in an upper room to a gospel movement that would spread throughout the Roman Empire and eventually the whole world.

01:07.930 --> 01:13.075
But it's not as if Jesus finished his work and then it's just up to the church to do their part.

01:13.676 --> 01:17.720
No, in fact, here's my one sentence summary of the book of Acts.

01:18.661 --> 01:23.826
Jesus advances his mission through the church by the power of the Spirit.

01:24.194 --> 01:25.136
That's the book of Acts.

01:25.937 --> 01:29.963
And you can see this in Acts 1, 8, which is like a thesis statement for the book.

01:30.344 --> 01:43.245
There, Jesus says to his disciples, you will receive power when the Holy Spirit has come upon you and you will be my witnesses in Jerusalem and Judea and Samaria and to the end of the earth.

01:44.387 --> 01:51.058
And that actually functions as a kind of table of contents for the entire book of Acts because then,

01:51.362 --> 01:55.667
Chapters one through seven, they're witnessing to Jesus in Jerusalem.

01:56.108 --> 02:00.533
In chapters eight through 12, they're witnessing to Jesus in Judea and Samaria.

02:00.853 --> 02:05.799
And then in chapters 13 through 28, they're going to the end of the earth.

02:06.600 --> 02:18.674
And what happens in the second half of the book, in chapters 13 to 28, is you have Paul's three missionary journeys that are going through the major urban centers of the Mediterranean world.

02:19.298 --> 02:26.410
And so where we come into the story today in Acts chapter 15 is the beginning of the second missionary journey.

02:27.031 --> 02:36.207
They just finished the first missionary journey where they traveled over a thousand miles all over the region of Galatia preaching the gospel and planting churches.

02:36.949 --> 02:37.810
And now

02:37.890 --> 02:50.644
They're back in Antioch where they're getting ready to set out on the second missionary journey where they're gonna revisit some of the earlier churches and then plant more churches in cities like Philippi, Thessalonica, and Corinth.

02:51.685 --> 02:55.990
And at one level, this passage that we're looking at today is amazing.

02:56.350 --> 02:59.834
I mean, the mission of Jesus breaks into a whole new part of the world.

03:00.615 --> 03:03.538
But on the other hand, it's very ordinary.

03:03.970 --> 03:12.083
It reads like a travel journal full of normal human challenges, like relational conflict, cultural tension, and hard decisions.

03:13.285 --> 03:16.590
And here's why I'm so excited for this ordinary passage.

03:17.211 --> 03:28.629
When we think of mission, we often think of big, heroic moments, like the apostles are filled with the spirit doing miracles before big crowds to the glory of God.

03:29.591 --> 03:31.474
But this passage reminds us

03:31.714 --> 03:35.880
The mission is not just heroic moments, it's ordinary faithfulness.

03:36.962 --> 03:39.766
It happens not just on Sundays, but every day.

03:39.787 --> 03:46.116
I think of a mom who prays for her kids every night, no spotlight, no stage, just faithfulness.

03:46.597 --> 03:47.238
That's mission.

03:47.999 --> 03:51.344
I think of someone who invites their coworker to lunch, to build a relationship.

03:51.364 --> 03:54.630
That's not dramatic, but that's how the gospel begins to move.

03:55.871 --> 03:57.554
And so the mission of Jesus

03:57.762 --> 04:01.847
moves forward through ordinary people navigating real life.

04:02.868 --> 04:05.951
And that means that you don't have to be an apostle to be a part of the mission.

04:06.632 --> 04:07.553
You don't need a stage.

04:07.873 --> 04:10.476
You're not required to have a dramatic conversion story.

04:10.516 --> 04:14.080
You just need to be faithful where God has called you.

04:15.402 --> 04:20.367
And so Jesus advances his mission through ordinary faithfulness in everyday life.

04:20.628 --> 04:22.830
That's what we're going to learn in this passage.

04:23.571 --> 04:24.672
So let me read this for us.

04:25.153 --> 04:26.354
I'm starting an ax.

04:26.498 --> 04:31.685
chapter 15 verse 36, and I'm going to read through chapter 16 verse 10.

04:34.028 --> 04:36.171
Acts chapter 15, starting in verse 36.

04:38.675 --> 04:46.245
And after some days, Paul said to Barnabas, let us return and visit the brothers in every city where we proclaimed the word of the Lord and see how they are.

04:46.285 --> 04:49.970
Now Barnabas wanted to take with him John called Mark.

04:50.370 --> 04:57.902
But Paul fought best not to take with them, one who had withdrawn from them in Pamphylia and had not gone with them to the work.

04:57.922 --> 05:01.588
And there arose a sharp disagreement so that they separated from each other.

05:02.069 --> 05:04.673
Barnabas took Mark with him and sailed away to Cyprus.

05:05.214 --> 05:10.041
But Paul chose Silas and departed, having been commended by the brothers to the grace of the Lord.

05:10.763 --> 05:14.148
And he went through Syria and Solisia, strengthening the churches.

05:15.150 --> 05:17.874
Paul came also to Derby and to Lystra.

05:18.242 --> 05:23.629
A disciple was there named Timothy, the son of a Jewish woman who was a believer, but his father was a Greek.

05:24.410 --> 05:27.254
He was well-spoken of by the brothers at Lestra and Iconium.

05:28.015 --> 05:35.766
Paul wanted Timothy to accompany him, and he took him and circumcised him because of the Jews who were in those places, for they all knew that his father was a Greek.

05:36.787 --> 05:44.818
As they went on their way through the cities, they delivered to them for observance the decisions that had been reached by the apostles and elders who were in Jerusalem.

05:45.026 --> 05:49.110
So the churches were strengthened in the faith and they increased in numbers daily.

05:49.150 --> 05:56.096
And they went through the region of Virginia and Galatia, having been forbidden by the Holy Spirit to speak the word in Asia.

05:56.737 --> 06:02.863
And when they had come up from Missia, they attempted to go into Bithynia, but the spirit of Jesus did not allow them.

06:03.723 --> 06:06.306
So passing by Missia, they went down to Troas.

06:07.707 --> 06:14.994
And a vision appeared to Paul in the night, a man of Macedonia was standing there urging him and saying, come over to Macedonia and help us.

06:15.618 --> 06:23.148
And when Paul had seen the vision immediately, we sought to go into Macedonia concluding that God had called us to preach the gospel to them.

06:23.889 --> 06:25.631
This is God's word, pray with me.

06:30.738 --> 06:35.624
God, we're here this morning because you are a missional God.

06:36.406 --> 06:42.834
You have chosen to enter into this broken world and pursue us in your love.

06:43.298 --> 06:53.033
And so God, we pray this morning that we would have an encounter with you, the living God, the loving God, the one who pursues us with mercy and grace.

06:54.034 --> 07:00.965
And God, we pray that that encounter would transform us and draw us into the beautiful work that you're doing in this city.

07:01.025 --> 07:06.413
And God, we thank you for epic moments, for dramatic stories.

07:06.493 --> 07:07.535
We see you in that.

07:08.316 --> 07:12.082
But God, we also pray that you would teach us to be faithful with little.

07:13.698 --> 07:19.704
to be faithful to you in quiet moments, in unseen moments.

07:20.584 --> 07:24.808
And God, we pray that in all of that, that your mission would advance throughout this city.

07:25.089 --> 07:28.552
We pray this in Jesus' name, amen, amen.

07:29.733 --> 07:35.218
All right, so this passage is teaching us that mission isn't just about bold personalities or dramatic moments.

07:35.759 --> 07:39.402
No, Jesus advances his mission through ordinary faithfulness.

07:40.103 --> 07:43.666
And throughout this passage, we're gonna see that in three ordinary

07:43.938 --> 07:45.019
areas of life.

07:45.119 --> 07:49.465
And the first is that Jesus advances his mission in conflict.

07:50.005 --> 07:54.231
And so we see this at the very beginning, pick up with me again in verse 36.

07:54.371 --> 08:06.846
It says, and after some days, after the first missionary journey, Paul said to Barnabas, let us return and visit the brothers in every city where we proclaim the word of the Lord and see how they are.

08:06.886 --> 08:11.972
So right out the gate, we learn a really key principle here for discipleship.

08:12.633 --> 08:13.554
And that is,

08:13.762 --> 08:18.150
Follow up, follow up is a key aspect of discipleship.

08:18.811 --> 08:24.481
Paul and Barnabas had gone and preached the gospel and planted churches and now he wants to follow up with them.

08:25.042 --> 08:26.645
And so that's really important for us.

08:27.186 --> 08:31.713
We pray for people, we share the gospel and then we follow up with them.

08:32.154 --> 08:32.855
How are you doing?

08:33.096 --> 08:34.338
How can I be praying for you?

08:34.679 --> 08:37.043
Hey, that thing I prayed for you about, how's that going?

08:37.123 --> 08:38.866
How can I keep praying for you?

08:39.490 --> 08:45.058
Paul's goal is not to create a flash, but to form disciples and rooted communities.

08:45.479 --> 08:48.724
And to do that requires a ministry of follow up.

08:49.485 --> 08:53.190
But as they set out, a problem arises.

08:53.551 --> 08:54.472
Look at verse 37.

08:55.834 --> 09:06.770
Now Barnabas wanted to take with them John called Mark, but Paul thought best not to take with them, one who had withdrawn from them in Pamphylia and had not gone with them to do the work.

09:07.202 --> 09:12.128
and there arose a sharp disagreement so that they separated from each other.

09:13.149 --> 09:26.746
So, what happens here is this guy named John Mark, or John called Mark, had traveled with them on their first journey, but for some reason he dropped out, he withdrew, and we don't know why.

09:26.786 --> 09:32.854
And so Barnabas wanted to take John Mark with them on their second missionary journey, and Paul didn't.

09:33.535 --> 09:36.338
And it simply says that they had a sharp

09:36.450 --> 09:37.431
disagreement.

09:38.152 --> 09:40.354
Now, this was a big deal.

09:40.815 --> 09:42.977
This isn't like a minor conflict.

09:43.618 --> 09:45.820
This is a massive conflict.

09:45.840 --> 09:47.322
I want you to feel the weight of this.

09:47.963 --> 09:51.146
Paul and Barnabas were incredibly close personally.

09:51.867 --> 09:59.555
I mean, when Paul became a follower of Jesus and nobody trusted him, Barnabas was the one who vouched for him and took him under his wing.

09:59.616 --> 10:05.522
These two men spent years traveling together, hundreds of miles on the road.

10:06.082 --> 10:11.669
They were close, and not only were they close personally, they were public partners in ministry.

10:12.350 --> 10:16.135
They led the church and Antioch together for a year.

10:16.155 --> 10:27.750
And if that's not enough, this public disagreement happens immediately after the most unifying event in the whole book of Acts, the Jerusalem Council, earlier in Acts 15.

10:28.671 --> 10:30.954
So this wasn't minor tension.

10:31.695 --> 10:32.536
It was painful.

10:33.097 --> 10:34.258
It was personable.

10:34.338 --> 10:38.144
personal, and it would have been deeply disappointing to everyone there.

10:39.446 --> 10:44.455
And it's clear that this disagreement between Paul and Barnabas, it wasn't about theology or character.

10:44.495 --> 10:47.219
It was a difference in opinion over strategy.

10:47.820 --> 10:50.004
Do you take John Mark on this mission or not?

10:51.266 --> 10:58.778
And yet what's interesting is that Luke, the author of Acts, he doesn't focus on the content of the disagreement.

10:58.798 --> 11:01.202
And he doesn't tell us who he thinks was right.

11:01.666 --> 11:10.418
Luke is not interested in who is right in the dispute, but that it results in two teams going out in different direction for mission.

11:11.139 --> 11:17.868
So pick up with me in verse 39 again, says, and there arose a sharp disagreement so that they separated from each other.

11:18.289 --> 11:26.400
Barnabas took Mark with him and sailed away to Cyprus, but Paul chose Silas and departed, having been commended by the brothers to the grace of the Lord.

11:26.820 --> 11:31.026
And he went through Syria and Cilicia, strengthening the churches.

11:31.522 --> 11:34.726
So again, Luke doesn't tell us who won the argument.

11:36.007 --> 11:38.410
What he tells us is where the gospel went next.

11:38.831 --> 11:42.576
Two teams, two directions, more ground covered.

11:42.636 --> 11:44.898
This wasn't a fracture, it was a multiplication.

11:44.938 --> 11:50.545
And so the mission doesn't stop because of conflict, it moves forward through it.

11:51.987 --> 11:55.932
And what amazes me is that Luke could have left this story out.

11:57.033 --> 11:59.276
Like he's telling the story of the early church.

11:59.616 --> 12:00.978
He could have left this out.

12:01.058 --> 12:01.819
and he didn't.

12:02.881 --> 12:09.371
He's not putting an Instagram filter on the early church or airbrushing the mission to make it appear polished and problem-free.

12:09.411 --> 12:13.517
He wants the church to know, mission is hard.

12:14.058 --> 12:14.939
It's messy.

12:14.959 --> 12:22.130
We are broken people who are declaring to other broken people that there is one who can make us whole.

12:23.298 --> 12:34.829
And so the book of Acts refuses to romanticize the mission, and instead, it invites us into a movement that's powerful and spirit-led, and yet is deeply human and costly and imperfect.

12:36.171 --> 12:42.216
And it reveals a God who advances his mission, not in spite of our conflict, but often through our conflict.

12:43.598 --> 12:51.986
And if this is happening in the book of Acts between two of the godliest people in the New Testament, then it's definitely gonna happen amongst us.

12:52.930 --> 12:55.233
But conflict isn't necessarily bad.

12:55.293 --> 12:57.515
It's a normal part of ministry and mission.

12:59.057 --> 13:03.282
Sometimes we look at the world and we see conflict and we wonder, where is God?

13:04.243 --> 13:08.107
Sometimes we look at the church and we see conflict and we wonder, where is God?

13:08.928 --> 13:13.513
Sometimes we look at our lives and we see conflict and we wonder, where is God?

13:15.735 --> 13:18.098
But this passage teaches us that God is right there.

13:18.178 --> 13:24.508
in the midst of the conflict, at work and all of it, advancing his mission, showing his patience and maturing his people.

13:25.890 --> 13:27.994
So what about for you personally?

13:29.296 --> 13:31.159
Where do you have conflict in your life?

13:31.739 --> 13:33.482
Some of you have conflict at work.

13:34.123 --> 13:36.146
Maybe God is using it to advance his mission.

13:37.028 --> 13:38.851
Some of you have conflict in your marriage.

13:39.311 --> 13:42.897
Maybe God is teaching you to love sacrificially instead of conditionally.

13:43.819 --> 13:46.002
Some of you have conflict in friendship.

13:46.242 --> 13:51.349
Maybe God is inviting you to pursue reconciliation instead of quiet resentment.

13:51.369 --> 13:53.071
Some of you have conflict in the church.

13:53.191 --> 13:57.497
Maybe God is surfacing deeper issues that need healing in community.

13:57.557 --> 14:01.001
God doesn't waste conflict.

14:01.342 --> 14:06.949
He uses it to multiply his mission and to display his patience.

14:08.091 --> 14:10.674
And so we have this sharp disagreement.

14:11.234 --> 14:19.027
from with Paul and Barnabas, and it's actually what results in the very beginning of Paul's second missionary journey.

14:19.848 --> 14:24.315
But I want to make two qualifications as we talk about this sharp disagreement.

14:24.395 --> 14:29.503
One is that you can't use this to justify being a jerk, okay?

14:30.104 --> 14:38.578
You can't be a person of conflict and say, well, clearly Paul and Barnabas disagreed, so it's fine for me to be a disagreeable person all the time.

14:38.850 --> 14:43.277
Okay, there's nothing indicated here that what they did was ungodly.

14:43.297 --> 14:46.241
They had a disagreement about strategy and mission.

14:46.862 --> 14:48.424
So you can't use this to be a jerk.

14:48.444 --> 14:54.032
The second thing is you can't use this to justify not sticking together through difficulty in community.

14:54.794 --> 14:59.060
So there is a time to agree to disagree and go separate ways.

14:59.420 --> 15:00.562
There is a time for that.

15:00.770 --> 15:12.066
But that comes in the context of what we've seen throughout acts that in order to discover true community, we have to be willing to stay when it's hard.

15:12.887 --> 15:14.590
We have to be willing to sacrifice.

15:14.610 --> 15:22.100
We have to be willing to meet people halfway and strive forward in relationships even when it's difficult.

15:23.682 --> 15:26.386
And so this story isn't minimizing conflict.

15:26.506 --> 15:29.010
It's showing that we can't let it derail the mission.

15:30.402 --> 15:35.449
And just so you know, because this is tense, this was a sharp disagreement.

15:36.090 --> 15:39.795
But just so you know, Paul and John Mark did reconcile.

15:40.536 --> 15:43.239
I mean, John Mark must have been hurt by this at some level.

15:43.299 --> 15:45.983
Paul did not want to bring him because he dropped out the last time.

15:46.684 --> 15:57.178
But later in the New Testament, Paul refers to John Mark and he refers to him as his fellow worker and talks about how useful he is for the mission of Christ.

15:58.680 --> 16:00.242
And then as for Barnabas,

16:00.706 --> 16:03.631
This is actually the last that we hear of Barnabas.

16:04.633 --> 16:09.441
At the end of Acts 15, he quietly walks off the stage of biblical history.

16:10.322 --> 16:14.850
And so, can we just pause to give Barnabas his flowers for a minute?

16:16.052 --> 16:19.858
I mean, Barnabas was a pillar of the early church.

16:20.194 --> 16:21.716
Think about what we saw so far.

16:21.736 --> 16:25.661
In Acts 4, he sells his property and gives the money to the church.

16:26.342 --> 16:31.409
In Acts 9, he takes Paul under his wing when nobody else believes him.

16:31.750 --> 16:35.014
In Acts 11, he leads the church in Antioch.

16:35.034 --> 16:40.001
That's the first multicultural church and becomes the hub of all these missionary movements.

16:40.441 --> 16:44.286
In Acts 13, he sets out on the first missionary journey with Paul.

16:45.007 --> 16:50.034
And then in Acts 15, he fades into the background as a model disciple maker.

16:50.562 --> 16:59.195
You know, the kingdom of God is full of Barnabas' faithful, generous, courageous people who don't need the spotlight to be significant.

17:01.057 --> 17:04.362
And so what do we learn from the first part of this passage?

17:04.863 --> 17:11.293
Well, Jesus advances his mission through ordinary faithfulness in everyday life, even in conflict.

17:12.334 --> 17:15.959
But conflict isn't the only everyday challenge here.

17:16.019 --> 17:20.466
There's another one that we face constantly, and that is cultural difference.

17:20.770 --> 17:24.235
different backgrounds, different customs, different assumptions.

17:25.157 --> 17:31.346
And if the gospel is going to move forward in a diverse world, it can't stay locked inside of one culture.

17:31.867 --> 17:33.530
And so second, we see this.

17:34.211 --> 17:38.598
Jesus advances his mission through ordinary faithfulness across cultures.

17:39.819 --> 17:46.530
And the early church, we have to be mindful of this, the early church developed in a very multicultural context.

17:47.131 --> 17:49.234
Think about it, you have Jews,

17:49.378 --> 17:55.068
in a society that was politically ruled by Rome and culturally shaped by Greece.

17:56.330 --> 17:58.654
So they lived in a multicultural society.

17:58.734 --> 18:06.208
Most of them spoke multiple languages and were very skillful in going back and forth into one context to the other.

18:07.209 --> 18:14.482
And so pick up with me in chapter 16, verse one, says this, Paul also came to Derby and Lystra.

18:14.882 --> 18:20.310
A disciple was there named Timothy, the son of a Jewish woman who was a believer, but his father was a Greek.

18:20.330 --> 18:23.295
He was well-spoken of by the brothers at Listra and Iconium.

18:24.196 --> 18:28.303
So we just said goodbye to Barnabas.

18:28.944 --> 18:32.589
And now we say hello to Timothy, a new character in this story.

18:32.629 --> 18:36.135
And Timothy will become a significant figure in the Bible.

18:36.235 --> 18:40.722
In fact, he goes on to co-author five New Testament letters with Paul.

18:40.834 --> 18:46.402
He has two books of the New Testament that are named after him, which are letters that Paul wrote to Timothy.

18:47.223 --> 18:51.149
And he becomes a key pastor in the church in Ephesus.

18:52.091 --> 18:55.576
But here we learn a little bit about Timothy's origin story.

18:56.217 --> 18:59.562
Here we're told that Timothy has a mixed ethnic background.

18:59.602 --> 19:02.546
His mother was Jewish and his father was Greek.

19:03.234 --> 19:08.441
And I know that many of you are mixed race or come from mixed cultural backgrounds.

19:08.501 --> 19:12.507
And that's difficult sometimes in conversations in our society about race.

19:12.527 --> 19:13.708
You don't know where you fit in.

19:14.269 --> 19:15.350
Timothy is your guy.

19:15.370 --> 19:16.812
He gets it.

19:17.593 --> 19:18.635
He totally gets it.

19:19.376 --> 19:24.643
And Timothy's mixed ethnic background isn't a minor detail of this story.

19:25.384 --> 19:29.770
But we have to remember what happened in chapter 15 right before this.

19:30.491 --> 19:32.914
The gospel is going to the nations

19:33.090 --> 19:38.818
And a dispute arises about whether people from other nations need to be circumcised like the Jews or not.

19:39.559 --> 19:48.170
And the core question, the question beneath the question here is, do you have to shed your culture and become culturally Jewish in order to be a Christian?

19:48.751 --> 19:49.933
That's what they were debating.

19:50.594 --> 19:55.420
And so the Jerusalem Council gives a definitive answer in chapter 15, and that is no.

19:55.440 --> 20:02.610
That the gospel is for all nations, and the church will be a community made up of every tribe, tongue, people, and nation.

20:03.266 --> 20:10.379
Every culture has beauty that reflects God's intent for creation, and it has brokenness that needs healing in Christ.

20:11.281 --> 20:20.939
And so as the gospel goes from the Jews to the Gentiles, Timothy, who is part Jew, part Gentile, will be a key bridge for the mission.

20:21.941 --> 20:24.626
So pick up then in verse three, it goes on and says,

20:25.154 --> 20:34.288
Paul wanted Timothy to accompany him, and he took him and circumcised him because of the Jews who were in those places, for they all knew that his father was a Greek.

20:35.490 --> 20:38.435
So, something really interesting happens here.

20:39.737 --> 20:43.082
Paul takes Timothy with him, and it says that he circumcises him.

20:43.122 --> 20:44.824
Now, Timothy's a grown man, okay?

20:45.325 --> 20:50.994
He's not a child, he's not an infant, so we're gonna talk about some real sacrifice for the mission of Christ here, okay?

20:51.074 --> 20:53.917
Timothy's a grown man, Paul circumcises him.

20:53.957 --> 21:05.090
And what's strange about this is that what we learn in Acts 15 is that circumcision is not required to become a follower of Jesus.

21:05.130 --> 21:08.814
You don't have to become culturally Jewish to be a Christian.

21:09.094 --> 21:18.024
And so if that's the case, and Paul is taking Timothy to actually spread the news of what they decided in Acts 15, then why in the world did Paul circumcise Timothy?

21:18.084 --> 21:19.826
That doesn't seem to make sense.

21:20.386 --> 21:21.247
Well, I'll tell you why.

21:21.847 --> 21:28.394
Because Paul isn't concerned with expressing his freedom, but rather laying down his cultural preferences for the mission.

21:29.475 --> 21:33.799
And in our culture, freedom means if I have a right, I should exercise it.

21:34.199 --> 21:37.683
My autonomy matters most or no one can tell me what to do.

21:38.784 --> 21:42.747
But for the Christian, freedom is not the right to do whatever I want.

21:43.428 --> 21:46.711
It's the ability to lay down what I want for the sake of love.

21:47.832 --> 21:49.714
This is what the Apostle Paul was all about.

21:50.178 --> 21:56.165
In 1 Corinthians 9, he says, I have become all things to all people, that by all means, I might save some.

21:56.225 --> 22:05.517
He says to the Jews, I became a Jew, to those under the law, as under the law, to those outside the law, as outside the law, to the weak, I became weak.

22:05.537 --> 22:11.204
And so this isn't compromise, it's cultural flexibility for the sake of mission.

22:11.244 --> 22:14.227
That's what he's doing with Timothy here.

22:14.828 --> 22:19.794
And cultural agility has always been an important

22:20.322 --> 22:22.467
skill for the church in mission.

22:23.771 --> 22:30.026
There's an academic named Andrew Walls, and Andrew Walls was one of the leading scholars of world Christianity in the last century.

22:30.066 --> 22:36.562
He taught at the University of Edinburgh and helped pioneer the academic study of global Christianity.

22:36.770 --> 22:44.918
So the church has been global and is increasingly global, but academics have basically focused on the West for a long time.

22:44.958 --> 22:46.940
And Andrew Wall's really helped broaden this.

22:47.561 --> 22:53.467
But after years of studying how the faith spread across continents, he made a simple but powerful observation.

22:54.528 --> 23:04.018
The story of Christian mission is the story not of changing the gospel, but transmitting it into new cultures, new languages, and new ways of understanding.

23:04.674 --> 23:07.477
So Christianity is not locked into one culture.

23:07.517 --> 23:12.223
The same gospel is embodied differently in a variety of cultures.

23:13.144 --> 23:15.347
And so think about how that's happened historically.

23:15.987 --> 23:24.657
The gospel moved from Jewish synagogues into Greek cities, from the Roman Empire into Celtic villages, from Europe into Africa into Asia.

23:24.998 --> 23:31.986
And every time it crossed a boundary, it didn't change its message, but it took root in new cultural soil.

23:32.834 --> 23:37.601
So Christian mission at its core requires cultural agility.

23:37.861 --> 23:52.402
We wouldn't be here if that wasn't the case because the gospel was translated and transmitted in one culture to the next to another, to a culture that we were in so that we could understand it and be transformed by the good news of Jesus.

23:52.674 --> 23:54.717
That's what we see in Acts 16.

23:54.757 --> 23:58.402
Timothy himself embodies that gospel transmission.

23:58.682 --> 24:03.589
Jewish mother, Greek father, the gospel is crossing boundaries again.

24:03.609 --> 24:13.363
And so this applies to us so much in Los Angeles, which is one of the most culturally diverse cities in the history of the world.

24:14.144 --> 24:19.391
I mean, LA is a melting pot of cultures, and it goes back to its original founding.

24:20.212 --> 24:21.554
In 1781,

24:22.018 --> 24:28.494
Spanish missionaries sent 44 people known as the Pobladores to establish the city of Los Angeles.

24:29.275 --> 24:35.410
But the Pobladores, they consisted of 11 families and had an incredible amount of ethnic diversity.

24:35.430 --> 24:38.738
I mean, these are the founders of the city of Los Angeles.

24:38.882 --> 24:41.145
And listen to the diversity of these 44 people.

24:41.165 --> 24:52.302
There were two Spaniards, two Africans, eight who were mixed Spanish and black, nine Native Americans, and one mestizo, which was a mix of Spanish and Native American.

24:53.183 --> 24:56.328
So our city has been a melting pot of culture from the very beginning.

24:56.388 --> 25:00.755
And today, there are 140 different countries represented in LA.

25:00.775 --> 25:03.940
And it's not just a few people from each.

25:04.741 --> 25:05.522
Did you know?

25:05.986 --> 25:10.891
that there are more Armenians living in Los Angeles than anywhere in the world outside of Armenia.

25:11.952 --> 25:15.775
Did you know that LA has the most Filipinos outside of the Philippines?

25:17.057 --> 25:20.540
LA has the most Salvadorians outside of El Salvador.

25:21.441 --> 25:30.930
LA has the most Guatemalans outside of Guatemala, the most Koreans outside of Korea, the most Vietnamese people outside of Vietnam, the most Cambodians outside of Cambodia.

25:31.691 --> 25:35.154
LA even has the most Australians outside of Australia.

25:36.002 --> 25:40.127
And of course, LA has the most Mexican people outside of Mexico.

25:40.167 --> 25:46.515
So if you want to see the gospel go to the nations, there's no better place to be than in the city of angels.

25:47.697 --> 25:55.827
But to be on mission here, you have to hold firmly to the gospel and also know how to translate it across cultures.

25:56.848 --> 26:01.554
But remember, we're talking about ordinary faithfulness here.

26:01.890 --> 26:10.966
So when I talk about cultural agility and translating the gospel, I'm not talking about being a missionary that goes to the Middle East and learns Arabic and words a hijab.

26:10.986 --> 26:11.768
That's amazing.

26:11.868 --> 26:13.431
Some people are going to be cold to that.

26:14.353 --> 26:17.378
I'm talking about ordinary faithfulness right here in this city.

26:18.280 --> 26:21.205
I'm talking about my neighbor who's Middle Eastern.

26:21.265 --> 26:26.194
How can I learn about his culture so that I can translate the gospel to his context?

26:26.690 --> 26:28.713
Or my other next door neighbor, who's Armenian.

26:28.753 --> 26:38.346
I think about how I've had Armenian brothers and sisters in our church who have helped me understand his culture and context so that I can build relationships, so that I can try and share the gospel with him.

26:38.406 --> 26:47.498
And then, of course, almost half of our city is, or maybe probably more than half of our city, is Spanish speaking.

26:48.779 --> 26:53.746
Por eso estoy aprendiendo español, y précte gartódos los días.

26:54.146 --> 27:19.122
For those of you who aren't tracking, I just said, that's why I'm learning Spanish and why I practice it every day because a lot of my neighbors only speak Spanish and I want to share the love of Jesus with them.

27:19.202 --> 27:24.431
We're talking about translating the gospel here, but of course this doesn't just apply to languages.

27:24.471 --> 27:30.903
I'm even talking about learning the neighborhoods that we live in and how to contextualize the gospel there.

27:31.784 --> 27:41.782
And so in our regional prayer coming up, we're asking the regions, the different regions in our city to identify the idols and opportunities in your region that you live in.

27:41.982 --> 27:44.306
And they're going to be very different from region to region.

27:44.770 --> 27:49.379
So in Santa Monica, there's going to be an idol of career success.

27:49.920 --> 27:52.925
The people are looking to that in place of God.

27:53.567 --> 27:56.131
But in Silver Lake, they're going to say, I don't care about a career.

27:56.773 --> 27:57.514
Like, what is that?

27:57.594 --> 27:59.959
Like, this is an expression of my soul, right?

27:59.979 --> 28:03.626
Like, in a Silver Lake, that's going to be an idol of authenticity.

28:03.666 --> 28:08.114
So my point is that to be on mission in this city,

28:08.674 --> 28:19.387
We have to learn the culture and translate the gospel to people in a way that makes sense to them, that challenges their idols and shows that Jesus is the true fulfillment of their loanings.

28:22.952 --> 28:27.117
But even when we're willing to cross cultures, there's still another challenge that we all face.

28:27.137 --> 28:30.281
It's one thing to know that we're called to mission.

28:30.321 --> 28:34.706
It's another thing to know where to go, what to do, and when to move.

28:35.266 --> 28:40.151
Because everyday mission isn't just about navigating conflict and crossing culture.

28:40.772 --> 28:44.376
It's also about making decisions when direction isn't clear.

28:44.456 --> 28:45.537
And that's what we see next.

28:46.318 --> 28:52.004
Jesus advances his mission through ordinary faithfulness amid uncertainty.

28:52.725 --> 28:53.626
That's what we're gonna see.

28:53.666 --> 28:56.749
They've begun the first missionary journey.

28:57.310 --> 28:58.010
Where do we go?

28:58.050 --> 28:59.592
Who do we talk to?

28:59.892 --> 29:03.236
They gotta make decisions of what's next and it's not easy.

29:03.676 --> 29:05.138
So look at verse six with me.

29:05.634 --> 29:13.782
says, and they went through the region of Phrygia and Galatia, having been forbidden by the Holy Spirit to speak the word in Asia.

29:14.523 --> 29:20.889
And when they had come up to Mysia, they attempted to go into Bithynia, but the spirit of Jesus did not allow them.

29:21.770 --> 29:33.362
So they want to go to Asia, which, by the way, doesn't refer to the whole continent of Asia, how we think of it, but to the Roman province of Asia, which is in modern day Turkey, they want to go there

29:33.538 --> 29:35.841
but it says the Holy Spirit forbids them.

29:36.763 --> 29:40.228
And then they want to go to Bithynia, which is also in modern day Turkey.

29:40.288 --> 29:43.393
And the spirit of Jesus does not allow them.

29:44.094 --> 29:48.821
So they're trying to advance the mission, but they don't know where to go.

29:48.841 --> 29:55.251
And so then pick up in verse eight, says, so passing by Messiah, they went down to Troas.

29:55.952 --> 30:02.802
And a vision appeared to Paul in the night, a man of Macedonia was standing there urging him and saying, come over to Macedonia and help us.

30:03.298 --> 30:10.870
And when Paul had seen the vision immediately, we sought to go into Macedonia, concluding that God had called us to preach the gospel to them.

30:11.911 --> 30:17.640
So Macedonia, we talked about, they wanted to go towards modern day Turkey.

30:18.061 --> 30:21.627
Macedonia was a Roman province in modern day Greece.

30:22.168 --> 30:24.772
And one of its leading cities was Philippi.

30:24.952 --> 30:27.095
We'll learn about that next week.

30:27.115 --> 30:31.442
But Paul has a vision of a man of Macedonia

30:31.522 --> 30:33.905
who beckons him to come there and help him.

30:34.887 --> 30:44.159
But the key is that in verse 10, that it says that after all of this, they concluded that God had called them there to Macedonia.

30:45.081 --> 30:47.544
And some people are gonna read these verses.

30:47.584 --> 30:51.790
And I want you to imagine like, how did this play out for them?

30:51.830 --> 30:52.551
What did it look like?

30:52.591 --> 30:57.197
It said that the Holy Spirit forbid them from going here in the spirit of Jesus, didn't allow them to go there.

30:57.237 --> 30:59.280
And then this man in the Macedonia calls him there.

30:59.320 --> 31:00.562
What did that look like?

31:00.898 --> 31:07.464
Well, some people read it and assume that the Holy Spirit literally showed up and said to them, do not go there.

31:07.484 --> 31:19.776
Or maybe they think that the Holy Spirit came and there was like this force field that the Holy Spirit set out and they tried to walk and like bounced off of it and the Holy Spirit's there like you shall not pass.

31:19.796 --> 31:20.437
You know, I don't know.

31:21.738 --> 31:29.586
They kind of assumed that that's how it played out, that they heard a voice or there was some kind of power, but it doesn't actually say that.

31:30.082 --> 31:33.207
I mean, we don't know how the Holy Spirit forbid them from going.

31:33.688 --> 31:35.671
Maybe the weather was too bad to travel there.

31:36.272 --> 31:38.635
Maybe the local officials wouldn't let them pass.

31:39.016 --> 31:39.617
We don't know.

31:39.657 --> 31:46.648
The point is, is that God closed that door, and then He closed another door, but then He opens another door.

31:47.850 --> 31:49.132
And He does that through a dream.

31:50.434 --> 31:58.066
And after all of this, Paul concludes that God had called us there.

31:58.178 --> 32:06.367
Being called by God doesn't just mean waiting for a voice, but walking through a process of discerning God's will for your life.

32:07.669 --> 32:08.630
That's what we're seeing here.

32:08.750 --> 32:11.553
Paul concluded after all of these things.

32:12.174 --> 32:17.800
So for you, maybe you're asking the question, how do I know where God is calling me for mission?

32:18.902 --> 32:26.130
Well, first of all, this passage assumes that when you're making big decisions in your life, that God's mission is a major factor in it.

32:26.754 --> 32:31.879
So it's not just do we move there because it's comfortable, but will we be on mission there?

32:33.100 --> 32:37.604
It's not just do I take that job, but is that a mission field that God is calling me to?

32:37.665 --> 32:45.752
It's not just do I marry this person because we get along well, but will we be an effective team for sharing the love of Christ?

32:47.254 --> 32:51.898
And so we need to discern God's will and mission plays a major part in that.

32:52.299 --> 32:55.762
And here's the typical approach I think that people have to

32:56.226 --> 32:57.508
discerning God's will.

32:57.568 --> 33:01.775
They either look for a sign or listen to it for a voice.

33:02.676 --> 33:04.499
So maybe God, where should I move?

33:04.539 --> 33:09.387
And they're praying and they open their eyes and they see a license plate from Vermont.

33:09.547 --> 33:11.030
God's calling me to Vermont.

33:11.511 --> 33:12.993
It's a sign from God.

33:13.634 --> 33:16.178
I mean, maybe it's a possibility, right?

33:17.026 --> 33:27.115
But the problem is that when people are either just looking for a sign or listening for a voice, sometimes when they do that, it's just mere superstition, kind of cloaked in spirituality.

33:27.997 --> 33:31.026
Like I think about when I was a kid, I had one of those magic eight balls.

33:31.166 --> 33:32.530
Anybody remember those?

33:32.738 --> 33:40.930
Is this thing that, you know, we don't have them today, but is this like magic eight ball and you would shake it up and it would give you different answers.

33:40.970 --> 33:44.014
So I'd be like, you know, I was like, should I do my homework?

33:44.054 --> 33:45.516
You know, shake it up.

33:45.616 --> 33:47.559
And they'd say, signs point to yes.

33:48.220 --> 33:52.266
I'm like, no, you misheard me shake it up again, you know, until you get something else.

33:52.286 --> 33:58.194
And a lot of people kind of approach God's will in that way, but God is not a magic eight ball.

33:58.306 --> 34:02.771
He's not hiding his will, trying to get you to figure it out so that you can be faithful to him.

34:03.311 --> 34:05.694
He's revealed his will of how you should live.

34:05.754 --> 34:13.002
He calls you to seek first his kingdom, and sometimes God may speak to you in ways that are undeniable.

34:13.883 --> 34:20.590
But whether that happens or not, a sense of calling must include a process of discernment.

34:21.290 --> 34:21.971
Let me say that again.

34:21.991 --> 34:24.754
A sense of calling

34:24.834 --> 34:29.200
must include a process of discernment.

34:29.861 --> 34:33.486
And I would say that that process should involve four different things.

34:34.447 --> 34:35.729
The first is scripture.

34:36.450 --> 34:40.755
What principles from the Bible would speak into a decision that you have to make?

34:41.096 --> 34:45.402
I mean, the Bible's not gonna answer your question, should I move to this city or should I take this job?

34:45.702 --> 34:51.570
But it is gonna tell you a lot of things that might shape your decision-making of what you wait in that process.

34:52.130 --> 34:53.211
So first is Scripture.

34:53.592 --> 34:56.335
Second thing you should take into account in decision-making is prayer.

34:57.336 --> 35:06.606
Scripture says that if we ask God for wisdom that He will give it to us from on high, we need to pray for wisdom and guidance throughout our decision-making process.

35:07.407 --> 35:09.870
Third in this process is community.

35:10.390 --> 35:21.042
If you're sensing a calling and then you're going through a process of discernment, you should involve other people, godly trusted people in your life.

35:21.282 --> 35:27.149
who would pray, who can ask you hard questions, who can go into that process of discernment with you.

35:28.251 --> 35:33.437
And then fourth, this process of discernment should be looking for God's providence.

35:33.978 --> 35:38.844
How do you see God's hand moving in your life and what he's been doing and where he's leading you?

35:38.884 --> 35:44.050
And how that helps you understand what doors he's closing and what doors he's opening.

35:44.866 --> 35:52.437
And so a sense of calling should be followed by a process of discernment that involves scripture, prayer, community, and providence.

35:52.938 --> 36:00.849
And hopefully you can get to a place where you can say with people who have been going through that process with you, it seems good to the Holy Spirit in us.

36:01.791 --> 36:03.273
That's what they did in Acts chapter 15.

36:03.293 --> 36:04.234
That's the goal.

36:04.274 --> 36:07.519
So I think about this even in my own life.

36:07.619 --> 36:12.466
I mean, in 2012, my wife and I were living in Chicago.

36:12.898 --> 36:18.306
And we sense the call to move to Los Angeles and to be a part of this church.

36:18.386 --> 36:40.176
But here's the thing, that process, it was about a nine month process of lots of prayers, lots of conversations, lots of what abouts, lots of what ifs, going back and forth between yes and no, like struggling, like working through it, in our own marriage, like a nine month process.

36:40.397 --> 36:41.458
And at the end of that,

36:41.858 --> 36:46.563
We could say with a clear sense that God is calling us to Los Angeles.

36:47.584 --> 36:50.367
But that wasn't just just hearing a voice and going.

36:50.387 --> 36:52.589
I mean, there was a process of that.

36:52.829 --> 36:55.051
And so that's what we see here in this passage.

36:55.532 --> 36:56.453
God closes the door.

36:57.133 --> 36:58.174
He closes another door.

36:58.214 --> 37:00.256
They're seeking the kingdom.

37:00.276 --> 37:01.037
They're on mission.

37:01.097 --> 37:03.199
They're pushing on doors and God opens a door.

37:03.780 --> 37:06.583
And they go to Macedonia towards Philippi.

37:07.584 --> 37:09.906
Now, I want to look at verse 10 again because

37:10.338 --> 37:13.162
There's something remarkable in verse 10 that I think you may have missed.

37:14.124 --> 37:24.779
Verse 10, it says this, and when Paul had seen the vision, immediately we sought to go into Macedonia, concluding that God had called us to preach the gospel to them.

37:25.721 --> 37:26.422
This is amazing.

37:26.462 --> 37:26.983
Did you see it?

37:27.624 --> 37:29.326
There's something amazing here.

37:29.386 --> 37:30.668
I'm afraid that you missed it.

37:31.730 --> 37:32.531
You didn't see it, did you?

37:33.212 --> 37:34.574
Okay, okay, let me explain it.

37:34.714 --> 37:35.415
Here's what happens.

37:35.495 --> 37:37.458
Listen, this is incredible, okay?

37:38.114 --> 37:42.601
We've been reading Acts, we've been in Acts for a year, 15 chapters.

37:43.442 --> 37:45.425
And Luke is the author of Acts.

37:45.625 --> 37:50.853
And for 15 chapters, Luke has been telling us about everything that happens in Acts.

37:51.154 --> 37:53.818
And everywhere he's spoken in the third person.

37:54.379 --> 37:57.864
Paul went here, he did this, Peter did this, they did that.

37:58.104 --> 37:58.986
It was about them.

37:59.026 --> 38:04.594
But here in verse 10, for the first time, he uses the first person.

38:05.026 --> 38:11.075
In verse 10, he says, immediately we sought to go into Macedonia.

38:11.095 --> 38:16.342
And then he goes on, he said, God has called us to preach the gospel to them.

38:16.362 --> 38:19.347
So think about what's been happening here with Luke.

38:19.747 --> 38:20.769
He heard about the mission.

38:20.809 --> 38:25.155
He wrote about the mission, but here he joins the mission.

38:25.195 --> 38:28.760
The they turn into a we.

38:28.800 --> 38:32.946
And this is exactly what I hope happens in our church today.

38:33.346 --> 38:36.892
For many of you, mission is a third person reality.

38:37.513 --> 38:38.835
They are sent out.

38:39.396 --> 38:41.199
They share the gospel with others.

38:41.500 --> 38:42.842
They make disciples.

38:43.523 --> 38:47.289
But today, you can do like Luke and join the mission yourself.

38:48.031 --> 38:50.074
We have a burden for the lost.

38:50.174 --> 38:51.577
We are praying for a city.

38:51.897 --> 38:54.802
We are talking with people about Jesus.

38:55.163 --> 38:59.570
This is Christ's mission, but he calls all of us into it, amen?

39:01.954 --> 39:03.816
And so this is what everyday mission looks like.

39:04.597 --> 39:06.679
Not just stadium, stages, and big moments.

39:07.399 --> 39:16.789
No, Jesus advances his mission through everyday faithfulness in navigating conflict, crossing cultural differences, and making spirit-led decisions.

39:18.390 --> 39:30.002
But we've spent all of our time today talking about mission, and we are sent to proclaim a message, that is our mission, to proclaim this message of the good news of the kingdom of God.

39:30.370 --> 39:33.874
We have to remember what that message is and what it's about.

39:34.915 --> 39:41.543
And we have to remember that we can't reflect this good news unless we first receive it.

39:42.564 --> 39:51.434
And so I want us to end by, we've been talking about getting the message out, but I want us to end by reminding ourselves of what this message is.

39:51.494 --> 39:58.642
And this is the good news that while we are stuck in our sins,

39:59.010 --> 40:10.950
While we are buried in our guilt and in our shame, while we are undone by the brokenness of this world, God's response is to look on us with compassion.

40:10.990 --> 40:18.844
And when God sees you and your brokenness, what he wants to do is draw near to you.

40:19.164 --> 40:24.914
That's his heart, is not to resist and move away, but to draw near to you.

40:25.250 --> 40:28.854
And so he pursues us in his love and in his mercy.

40:28.874 --> 40:33.058
I know that we're talking about the mission that God has given us in this city.

40:33.098 --> 40:36.841
But we gotta start with God's mission towards us.

40:37.782 --> 40:41.766
He is so passionate about you that he sent his own son.

40:41.786 --> 40:47.472
And Jesus lived a life where he embodied the mercy and justice of God.

40:47.492 --> 40:53.778
He showed what perfect love and holiness and justice looks like in a life.

40:54.338 --> 40:56.001
Jesus touched the lepers.

40:56.782 --> 41:00.188
He pursued those who were on the outskirts of society.

41:00.428 --> 41:08.422
He confronted the hypocrites and then he took his perfect life and he offered it up as a sacrifice on the cross.

41:09.343 --> 41:20.722
He died bearing our sin, bearing our shame and our guilt so that you can be forgiven, so that you can be washed clean,

41:21.282 --> 41:29.552
so that you can be declared righteous, not because of what you do for God, but because of what God has done for you in Christ.

41:30.073 --> 41:31.094
It's pure grace.

41:31.835 --> 41:38.663
It's just because God is loving, because he's abounding in love for you, not just for humanity in general, but for you.

41:38.723 --> 41:40.425
He died for your sins.

41:40.786 --> 41:43.269
And it doesn't end there that he rose from the grave.

41:44.130 --> 41:50.738
So that when we talk about Jesus, we're not just looking back at a historic figure trying to obey his teachings.

41:51.138 --> 41:56.426
We can know a living savior who transforms us from the inside out.

41:56.446 --> 41:57.808
He rose from the grave.

41:58.428 --> 42:07.141
He ascended to the right hand of the Father, and then he poured out his Holy Spirit so that we could be a part of his mission moving forward.

42:07.221 --> 42:16.795
Jesus is advancing his mission, and he's doing it through the church all over the world, empowered by the spirit, and he's doing it right here in Los Angeles.

42:18.417 --> 42:19.218
Praise God.

42:21.826 --> 42:23.588
And we get to be a part of this.

42:25.291 --> 42:27.233
And I see something happening in our city.

42:27.954 --> 42:29.977
I see people hungry for the gospel.

42:30.618 --> 42:40.191
I see people who are not only open but eager and curious who are asking questions and showing up at church and looking for God.

42:41.293 --> 42:42.975
I don't want to miss this moment.

42:43.876 --> 42:46.340
I don't want you to miss this moment.

42:46.360 --> 42:48.082
Jesus is on the move.

42:48.418 --> 42:52.883
He's transforming people's lives and he invites us into that.

42:54.125 --> 42:59.731
And so I want us to be recipients of the gospel first before we then reflect it.

43:00.492 --> 43:04.817
So to my brothers in here, let me remind you, you were a son before you were a soldier.

43:05.979 --> 43:11.765
Yes, God has worked for you to do, but he saves you to himself and he delights in you.

43:12.887 --> 43:15.730
For the ladies in here, you were a daughter before you were a doer.

43:16.386 --> 43:19.991
that you can do all kinds of things to help other people and glorify God.

43:20.051 --> 43:23.616
But you're first and foremost, the daughter of the king and he delights in you.

43:24.517 --> 43:32.208
And it's from that very place of being with God, abiding in him, that we then join in on his mission.

43:32.949 --> 43:34.070
So it's just the overflow.

43:34.731 --> 43:36.073
It's the overflow of our joy.

43:36.133 --> 43:38.456
It's the overflow of our freedom.

43:38.496 --> 43:43.403
It's the overflow of our peace in Christ and wanting to share that with others around us.

43:44.204 --> 43:45.586
And sometimes it's gonna happen

43:45.954 --> 43:49.118
in dramatic heroic moments and praise God for those.

43:50.299 --> 43:56.186
But most of the time it's gonna happen through our quiet faithfulness, trusting Jesus every day.

43:56.767 --> 43:57.248
Pray with me.

43:58.349 --> 44:06.259
God, we thank you so much for your sacrificial pursuit of us, your mission to us.

44:07.801 --> 44:10.524
Lord, I pray that we would just be overwhelmed by your grace.

44:11.665 --> 44:15.570
I pray for anyone here today that doesn't know you as Lord and Savior

44:16.450 --> 44:27.443
that they would open themselves to you, that they would confess their sin, that they would trust in you and accept you as Lord and Savior, and that they would commit to following you all the days of their life.

44:29.205 --> 44:44.242
Lord, I pray for all of us who have done that, that you would help us to receive your grace and then reflect it to this world, and to see how your spirit is invading every aspect of our lives.

44:45.090 --> 44:49.096
our workplaces, our homes, our neighborhoods, where we hang out.

44:50.037 --> 44:50.558
You're there.

44:50.598 --> 44:51.419
You're at work.

44:51.760 --> 44:53.402
We're surrounded by people who need you.

44:53.442 --> 44:55.225
And so would you give us wisdom?

44:55.505 --> 44:56.506
Would you give us boldness?

44:56.586 --> 44:57.648
Would you give us courage?

44:59.090 --> 45:02.956
But Lord, ultimately, we pray that you would move and that you would save the lost.

45:04.398 --> 45:10.226
We pray that you would draw us into that work that would be a people who follow up, who...

45:10.434 --> 45:15.585
Share the good news of your son, Jesus, who pray for people who meet their needs physically, spiritually.

45:15.625 --> 45:18.371
And Lord, we will give you all the glory for that.

45:18.712 --> 45:19.393
It's your mission.

45:19.774 --> 45:20.536
It's for your glory.

45:20.616 --> 45:21.899
We pray this in your son's name.

45:22.380 --> 45:22.700
Amen.

45:23.222 --> 45:25.206
Amen.

45:25.226 --> 45:26.068
Thank you for listening.

45:26.649 --> 45:30.898
For more audio and video content, please visit realityla.com.

